  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the difference between high fidelity and actual design?",
  "response": "High fidelity (hi-fi) design and actual design are terms used in the design process, often in the context of user experience (UX) and user interface (UI) design. They refer to different stages and levels of detail in the design process. Here's a breakdown of the differences:\n\n### High Fidelity Design:\n1. **Definition**: High fidelity design refers to a detailed and polished version of a design that closely resembles the final product. It includes all the visual elements, interactions, and content that will be present in the actual product.\n\n2. **Purpose**: The purpose of high fidelity design is to provide a realistic representation of the final product for stakeholders, developers, and users to review and test.\n\n3. **Features**:\n   - **Detailed Visuals**: Includes colors, typography, icons, images, and other visual elements.\n   - **Interactivity**: May include clickable prototypes with functional interactions and transitions.\n   - **Content**: Uses real or realistic content, including text, images, and multimedia.\n   - **Responsive Design**: Often includes designs for different screen sizes and devices.\n\n4. **Tools**: Tools like **Figma**, **Sketch**, **Adobe XD**, and **InVision** are commonly used to create high fidelity designs.\n\n### Actual Design:\n1. **Definition**: Actual design refers to the final, implemented version of the design that is used in the live product. This is the design that end-users interact with when they use the product.\n\n2. **Purpose**: The actual design is what the product looks and behaves like in real-world use. It has been developed, tested, and deployed.\n\n3. **Features**:\n   - **Functional**: Fully functional and interactive, with all features and elements in place.\n   - **Optimized**: Performance-optimized for speed, accessibility, and usability.\n   - **Live Content**: Uses real content that is being served to users.\n   - **Coding**: Built using actual code (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, etc.) and integrated with the backend systems.\n\n4. **Tools**: Actual design is developed using **front-end development tools** like **VS Code**, **Webpack**, **React**, **Angular**, etc., and is deployed on live servers.\n\n### Key Differences:\n- **Stage in Process**: High fidelity design is a prototype stage, while actual design is the final, live stage.\n- **Functionality**: High fidelity designs may simulate interactions, but actual designs are fully functional.\n- **Audience**: High fidelity designs are reviewed by stakeholders and tested by users; actual designs are used by the end-users.\n- **Content**: High fidelity designs use placeholder or realistic content; actual designs use real content.\n- **Development**: High fidelity designs are created using design tools; actual designs are built using code and deployed.\n\n### Example:\n- **High Fidelity Design**: A clickable prototype of a mobile app created in Figma, showing how the app will look and behave.\n- **Actual Design**: The live mobile app available on the App Store or Google Play that users can download and use.\n\nIn summary, high fidelity design is a detailed prototype that simulates the final product, while actual design is the final, fully-functional product that is live and in use.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
